Definition doesn't match but object type does.  The subject represents the actual minimum value of the measured variable, whereas the object represents the minimum permissible value, which may in fact differ from the actual minimum value.

Definitions match but object type is broader.  An exact match between the subject and object is formed when the object's "function" attribute (/element(*,PhysicalType)/distribution/online/url/@function) has a value of "download". See: https://eml.ecoinformatics.org/schema/eml-resource_xsd.html#OnlineType_url

No match can be found.  There is no single field that lists the format type for a data object in the EML standard. Rather, EML offers a choice of four data types within which properties provide information for a user to download and parse it.

Definitions match but object type is narrower.  Requires logic to determine if the upper and lower bounds match to form a single value. Unequal object values will not be averaged since this would modify the information.  Note, it appears the subject assumes the spatial reference system "WGS 84" and is therefore unclear if this requirement is met by EML. For this reason the match type is given a low confidence.
Definitions match but object type is broader.  Requires the concatenation of the object properties in the listed order and with a blank space separator.

Definitions match but object type is broader.  The object definition recommends a format, but does not enforce it. Therefore an ideal solution is an algorithm capable of identifying probable formats and converting them to the subject.  Assuming the object's recommended format, conversion entails reversing the order of lon/lat values to lat/lon, replacing comma delimiters with spaces, and ensuring the first and final points are identical.
